The everyday commands.

Compose commands mirror the single-container verbs from module three, but they operate on the whole project at once. Here are the ones you'll live in.

Docker compose up creates and starts every service; add dash d for detached. Docker compose up, dash d, dash dash build, rebuilds the build images first, then starts. Docker compose down stops and removes the containers and the project network; add dash v to also remove named volumes. Docker compose p-s lists the project's containers and their state. Docker compose logs tails the logs, for all services or one, with dash f to follow. Docker compose exec runs a command inside a running service, the Compose equivalent of docker exec. Docker compose run, dash dash r-m, spins up a new container of a service to run one command, useful for one-shot tasks like migrations. And docker compose config prints the fully-resolved y-a-m-l, after variable substitution and overrides.

Two distinctions are worth burning in early. First, exec versus run. Exec runs a command inside an already-running service container, so you'd use it to debug a live web app. Run starts a fresh, separate container of that service, for a one-shot job, like running database migrations; it doesn't touch the running one. Reach for exec to inspect, and run to do a task.

Second, config is your debugger. Before puzzling over why a variable didn't substitute, or an override didn't apply, run docker compose config. It prints the final y-a-m-l that Compose actually uses, with all the dot-env substitution and file merging resolved. It's the fastest way to see what Compose thinks you asked for. Everything else, build, pull, stop, and start, does exactly what the single-container verb did, just scoped to the whole project.
